I don't really like this song, the art and directing style is beautiful. Hayley, your voice is beautiful as always. The story telling elements are great. The lyrics and the notes are chaotic and don't feel like your usual writing style.


As I watch this and observe the ups and downs in Hayley's career, I'm worried that she doesn't have actual friends who care about her. She mentioned at her concert here last year that "Misguided Ghosts" is a song Paramore brought back out of the shelf because Hayley connected with it in her recent time...I loved this song and the album "Brand New Eyes" helped me get through the hardest time of my life, each song spoke about a specific issue I felt that I was dealing with. For that I feel like Hayley (the main writer for the album) connected with me as a kindred spirit. I know what it's like to wear a mask. And the foolish think you can change that mask to make others happy. You wear the mask to protect others, not for yourself. It helps you by not facing as much opposition from others and it helps you find like minded individuals who truly respect you and don't want to see any harm come to you.


I know this is left field for a youtube comment, but I feel I owe a great debt to Paramore for helping me get through a dangerous part of my life and set me back on my feet, I don't keep up with them as much as I used to. A lot of the newer songs that Hayley is writing worry me about her spirit. So I'll extend an olive branch, I'm open to talk if you need a stranger to talk to.

snippet.textDisplay:
I get the feeling that hayley has been through something traumatic, i felt so much raw emotion from this song and the video. I feel like This is pain she thought she could just push down, but it started following her and consuming her thoughts and running and isolation and fear seemed to be her everything. This is a pain she wouldn't wish on anyone, and i get the feeling that it really broke her down, but that she was able to transmute that pain (probably into this song) and regain her strength and composure. Rage is an intense emotion and when used correctly it can push you through to where you need to go next, but it can also be all consuming. I feel this is all about breaking cycles, and realizations. Realising that destroying another is destroying yourself, that even though you've (hayley) been hurt, by holding onto that pain without acknowledging it (running) youre creating another issue within yourself, youre hurting yourself. The strength needed to overcome the figure that was following her is necessary, it proves to her that she is capable of overcoming this pain. But this feels like the moment in spiritual awakening(s) where you realise the thing youve been fighting has really been yourself, or constructed by you the whole time. The shadow self has many lessons to teach. We are both the runner and the chaser, the light and the dark, the hunter and the hunted. Every action we take on another is a catalyst for another action happening upon us
Thats my interpretation anyways, I'm clairsentient/clairaudient/clairvoyant and a lot of these messages came rushing in while consuming this piece of art, it honestly brought me to tears.

snippet.textDisplay: I thought the song was really nice and catchy and was just enjoying the whole thing... but when she got to that line about who I assume abused her, I started shaking. I was not expecting this song to bring up those feelings of anger and pain coming from the abuse I've gone through, which is kind of what the song is all about- not knowing when you'll feel that rage. I love this song because it's not only very inherently beautiful, but it makes feel in control of my emotions surrounding my trauma (I know that's corny considering that's sort of the whole thing the song is saying). It's funny, I only listened to this song cause it was an add and it intrigued me(didn't realize it was hayley William's till halfway through).
